		<body>
			<p>My dear Sisters&#44;&#42;</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">I hope that these lines will<lb/> find you in good health.  We are well<lb/> here and I hope that we may enjoy<lb/> many more years.  I am engaged.<lb/>  <del>&#63;</del> And pretty<lb/> far from here.  <persName>Kahn</persName> from <placeName>M&#252;nster</placeName><lb/> proposed this engagement.  My bride<lb/> is also related to him.  Her brother<lb/> is married to the widow <persName>Lowenstein<lb/> Ahans</persName> &#40;&#63;&#41;&#44; the man who fell from the<lb/> attic.  His name <sic>isthe</sic> same as his<lb/> father&#44; <persName>Jacob</persName>.  The wife of <persName>Mr. Mastbaum</persName><lb/> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> is the sister of my<lb/> future sister&#45;in&#45;law.  She has a<lb/> sister.  Maybe you know her through<lb/> <persName>Simon</persName>.  When you see her&#44; tell her<lb/> that <persName>Werther</persName> send her his regards.<lb/>  Let her see the engagement announcement.<lb/>  It has not yet been settled when the<lb/> marriage will be.  I wish you were<lb/> here.  Let me hear from you as soon<lb/> as possible.</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">I remain your loving brother&#44;</p>
		  <p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">Lipman Elkus</persName>.</p>
			<p>I have been in <placeName>Rheine</placeName> last week.  T<lb/> They are all well satisfied.</p>

			<p>&#42;<persName>Sarah</persName> &amp; <persName>Zipporah Elkus</persName> visiting their uncle <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName><lb/> in <placeName>Phila.</placeName>  &#42;&#42;<persName role="author">Lipman Elkus</persName> born about <date>1835</date>. &#40;See letter <placeName>Phila.</placeName> <date>May 30&#44; 42</date><lb/> of <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName> to <persName>Zalma Rehine</persName>&#41;<lb/>  The three <persName>Elkus&#39;</persName> are the children of <persName>Leah Leeser</persName> &#40;sister of <persName>Isaac</persName>&#41;</p>
